<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-12-13T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-12-13T14:00:00-05:00" n="187" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d187">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">123W85/171: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss></hi><note n="13" xml:id="d187fn13">Sent via the Embassy at Paris as No.
                                9331.</note></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-12-13T14:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">December 13,
                                        1919, 2 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>Mission’s 5478, November 29, 6 p.m.</p>
                        <p>For Wood. You are assigned to Mr. Dresel’s mission. Upon his departure
                            for Berlin you may in his discretion proceed Munich unofficially and
                            temporarily for observation purposes. You should not however establish
                            consular office.</p>
                        <p>Same for Stewart changing Munich to Hamburg.<note n="14" xml:id="d187fn14">By telegram No. 3876, Nov. 24, 3 p.m., to the
                                Commission, the suggestion that Consul Sauer be stationed at Cologne
                                was approved (File No. 123W85/168).</note></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>